---

---

<section id="landscape" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:text-4xl dark:text-neutral-50"
    >
      The landscape
    </h2>
    <p
      class="mt-6 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-600 dark:text-neutral-400"
    >
      A handful of meta-harnesses are taking shape across the industry, each
      approaching the problem from a different starting point.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-6xl">
    <div class="grid items-stretch gap-6 lg:grid-cols-3">
      <div
        class="flex flex-col rounded-xl border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-100/60 p-8 sm:p-10 dark:border-neutral-800 dark:bg-neutral-900/40"
      >
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
          By Nx
        </p>
        <h2 class="mt-4" data-no-anchor>
          <img
            src="/images/polygraph-lockup-light-bg.svg"
            alt="Polygraph"
            width="678"
            height="137"
            class="block h-8 w-auto sm:h-9 dark:hidden"
          />
          <img
            src="/images/polygraph-lockup-dark-bg.svg"
            alt="Polygraph"
            width="678"
            height="137"
            class="hidden h-8 w-auto sm:h-9 dark:block"
          />
        </h2>
        <p
          class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
        >
          Polygraph focuses on cross-repo coordination and memory. It gives your
          agents a unified dependency graph across your organization without
          moving any code, durable sessions anyone can resume, and institutional
          memory that carries from one session to the next. It runs behind
          whatever harness you use, so that shared context follows your agents no
          matter which one drives them.
        </p>
        <a
          href="https://trypolygraph.com"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 self-start rounded-md border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-900 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-neutral-700 dark:border-neutral-700 dark:bg-neutral-100 dark:text-neutral-950 dark:hover:bg-white"
        >
          Explore Polygraph
          <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>

      <div
        class="flex flex-col rounded-xl border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-100/60 p-8 sm:p-10 dark:border-neutral-800 dark:bg-neutral-900/40"
      >
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
          By Databricks
        </p>
        <h2
          class="mt-4 flex h-8 items-center gap-2.5 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:h-9 sm:text-4xl dark:text-neutral-50"
          data-no-anchor
        >
          <img
            src="/images/omnigent-logo.svg"
            alt=""
            width="1024"
            height="1024"
            class="h-7 w-7 sm:h-8 sm:w-8"
          />
          Omnigent
        </h2>
        <p
          class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
        >
          Omnigent focuses on swapping harnesses and governing them. It puts
          Claude Code, Codex, Cursor, OpenCode, and Pi behind one interface you
          change in a single line, then enforces guardrails in code, not prompts:
          spend caps, approval gates, and OS-level sandboxing. Sessions run in
          the cloud and are shareable and co-drivable in real time.
        </p>
        <a
          href="https://github.com/omnigent-ai/omnigent"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 self-start rounded-md border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-900 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-neutral-700 dark:border-neutral-700 dark:bg-neutral-100 dark:text-neutral-950 dark:hover:bg-white"
        >
          Explore Omnigent
          <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>

      <div
        class="flex flex-col rounded-xl border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-100/60 p-8 sm:p-10 dark:border-neutral-800 dark:bg-neutral-900/40"
      >
        <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
          By SuperagenticAI
        </p>
        <h2
          class="mt-4 flex h-8 items-center text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-900 sm:h-9 sm:text-4xl dark:text-neutral-50"
          data-no-anchor
        >
          metaharness
        </h2>
        <p
          class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-700 dark:text-neutral-300"
        >
          metaharness focuses on optimizing a single harness rather than
          orchestrating many. An outer loop asks a coding agent to improve the
          scaffolding around a model, instruction files, setup flows, validation
          and test scripts, routing logic, then scores each proposal and keeps
          the best. Every candidate is snapshotted to disk, so the search stays
          reviewable. It's an open take on the Stanford Meta-Harness paper.
        </p>
        <a
          href="https://github.com/SuperagenticAI/metaharness"
          target="_blank"
          rel="noopener"
          class="mt-8 inline-flex items-center gap-2 self-start rounded-md border border-neutral-300 bg-neutral-900 px-5 py-2.5 text-sm font-medium text-white transition-colors hover:bg-neutral-700 dark:border-neutral-700 dark:bg-neutral-100 dark:text-neutral-950 dark:hover:bg-white"
        >
          Explore metaharness
          <span aria-hidden="true">&rarr;</span>
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
